Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law prohibits a person from driving or physically controlling a vehicle or operating
2 or physically controlling a vessel under certain circumstances if the person has specified amounts
3 of certain prohibited substances in his or her blood or urine. (NRS 484C.110, 488.410) Sections
4 5 and 15 of this bill additionally prohibit a person from driving or physically controlling a
5 vehicle or operating or physically controlling a vessel with specific amounts of fentanyl [or
6 methylenedioxymethamphetamine] in his or her blood or urine. Section 3 of this bill makes a
7 conforming change to include fentanyl [and methylenedioxymethamphetamine] in the definition
8 of “prohibited substance.”
9 [Existing law also prohibits a person from driving or physically controlling a vehicle or
10 operating or physically controlling a vessel under certain circumstances if the person has
11 specific amounts of marijuana or marijuana metabolite in his or her blood and the offense is
12 punishable as a felony. (NRS 484C.110, 484C.400, 488.410, 488.427) Sections 5 and 15
13 expand the applicability of the prohibition concerning the specific amounts of marijuana and
14 marijuana metabolite, thereby making the prohibition also applicable to offenses punishable as
15 a misdemeanor.
16 Additionally, existing law prohibits a person from driving or physically controlling a
17 vehicle or operating or physically controlling a vessel under certain circumstances if the
18 person is found by a measurement within 2 hours after driving or physically controlling the
19 vehicle or operating or physically controlling the vessel to have a concentration of alcohol of
20 0.08 or more on his or her breath, or 0.04 or more but less than 0.08 for commercial motor
21 vehicles. (NRS 484C.110, 484C.120, 484C.130, 484C.430, 488.410, 488.420, 488.425)
22 Sections 5-7 and 14-17 of this bill make various changes to account for the circumstance
23 under which a person drives or physically controls a vehicle or operates or physically controls
24 a vessel under certain circumstances and is found, after being involved in a crash or collision,
25 as applicable, to have the specified concentration of alcohol on his or her breath. Sections 19-
26 23, 28, 29 and 31 of this bill make conforming changes to account for certain organizational

