27 changes made in section 5. Section 4 of this bill makes certain changes concerning when a
28 person is presumed to be in physical control of a vehicle involved in a crash.]
29 Existing law establishes various penalties applicable to the offense of driving or
30 physically controlling a vehicle while under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited substance,
31 depending on whether the offense is the first, second or third offense within 7 years. (NRS
32 484C.400) Among other things, a court may sentence a person who is found guilty of a
33 second offense within 7 years to: (1) imprisonment for not less than 10 days nor more
34 than 6 months in jail; or (2) residential confinement for not less than 10 days nor more
35 than 6 months. Section 12 of this bill [makes various changes to increase certain penalties
36 and other sanctions applicable to a first or second offense.] increases the minimum term of
37 imprisonment or residential confinement to 20 days.
38 Existing law requires an offender who had a concentration of alcohol of 0.18 or more in
39 his or her blood or breath at the time of an offense to be evaluated before sentencing to
40 determine whether the offender has an alcohol or substance use disorder. (NRS 484C.350)
41 Section 11 of this bill reduces the concentration of alcohol threshold to require an offender
42 who had a concentration of alcohol of 0.16 or more in his or her blood or breath at the time of
43 the offense to be evaluated for an alcohol or substance use disorder. Sections 1, [2 and] 9 and
44 12 of this bill make conforming changes to reduce references to the concentration of alcohol
45 from 0.18 to 0.16. Section 38 of this bill makes a technical change to repeal a definition
46 that is not used in chapter 484C of NRS.
47 Additionally, existing law, under certain circumstances, authorizes certain first, second
48 and third-time offenders to apply to the court to undergo a program of treatment for an alcohol
49 or other substance use disorder. (NRS 484C.320, 484C.330, 484C.340) Existing law prohibits
50 an offender from applying to undergo such a program for third-time offenders if the offender
51 has previously applied to receive such treatment or has previously been convicted of certain
52 offenses. (NRS 484C.340) Section 10 of this bill removes the restriction related to previous
53 applications by a third-time offender to undergo such a program and instead prohibits the
54 offender from applying to undergo such a program if the offender has previously been ordered
55 to complete a program of treatment for third-time offenders.
56 For the purposes of determining whether a person that drives or physically controls a
57 vehicle while under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited substance is a first, second or
58 third-time offender, existing law qualifies an offense as a prior offense if it is: (1) evidenced
59 by a conviction; or (2) conditionally dismissed or the judgment of conviction is set aside or
60 dismissed in connection with successful completion of a diversionary program or specialty
61 court program. (NRS 484C.400) Section 12 [of this bill] additionally provides that an offense
62 qualifies as a prior offense if the person is undergoing a program of treatment for an alcohol
63 or substance use disorder for a first, second or third-time offender.
64 Existing law establishes a penalty that is applicable to a person who has previously
65 committed certain felonies related to driving under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited
66 substance and who subsequently commits the offense of driving or physically controlling a
67 vehicle while under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited substance. (NRS 484C.410)
68 Section 13 of this bill additionally applies this penalty to a person who is undergoing a
69 program of treatment for an alcohol or substance use disorder for a third-time offender, if the
70 person subsequently commits the offense of driving or physically controlling a vehicle while
71 under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited substance.
72 [Existing law requires certain conduct related to driving under the influence of alcohol or
73 a prohibited substance to have taken place “on a highway or on premises to which the public
74 has access.” (NRS 484C.110, 484C.120, 484C.150, 484C.160) Existing law also requires
75 certain other conduct related to driving under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited
76 substance to have taken place “on or off the highways of this State.” (NRS 484C.130,
77 484C.430) Sections 7 and 14 of this bill replace the phrase “on or off the highways of this
78 State” with “on a highway or premises to which the public has access” for consistency
79 throughout provisions governing driving under the influence of alcohol or a prohibited
80 substance.
81 Existing law provides that a blood test related to a person accused of driving or physically
82 controlling a vehicle or operating or physically controlling a vessel while under the influence
83 of alcohol or a prohibited substance is not admissible unless the blood test was performed by a
84 person who meets certain qualifications using certain medical standards. (NRS 484C.250,
85 488.500) Section 38 of this bill repeals those provisions relating to the admissibility of blood

